              <p>
                Big jackpots are advertised as an
                <strong>annuity value</strong> paid over many years (often 30).
                If you choose the <strong>cash option</strong>, you receive a
                reduced <em>lump sum</em>, typically around 60% of the
                advertised jackpot.
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">Lump sum estimate</p>
                <p>
                  <code>lump_sum ≈ jackpot × lump_sum_percentage</code><br />
                  Example: $500M jackpot, 60% cash value →
                  <code>$500M × 0.60 = $300M</code>
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>2. Federal lottery tax</h3>
              <p>
                For U.S. citizens and residents, the lottery operator must
                withhold <strong>24% federal income tax</strong> on prizes of
                $5,000 or more. However, your
                <strong>actual federal tax</strong> may be higher because
                lottery winnings are taxed as ordinary income and can push you
                into the top tax bracket.
              </p>
              <p>This calculator shows both:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Mandatory withholding</strong> (24% of the prize), and
                </li>
                <li>
                  An <strong>approximate final federal tax</strong> using a
                  simplified top marginal rate based on your filing status and
                  other income.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>3. State lottery tax</h3>
              <p>State treatment varies widely:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Some states have <strong>no income tax</strong> (e.g.,
                  Florida, Texas).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Some tax lottery winnings at their normal income‑tax rate.
                </li>
                <li>A few states have special rules or local taxes.</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                We use a <strong>single effective state rate</strong> for each
                state to keep the tool simple. It is an approximation, not an
                official rate.
              </p>

              <h3>4. Effective tax rate and after‑tax winnings</h3>
